            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Born in Chi\u0219in\u0103u, Moldova, in the final, turbulent years of the Soviet Union, Svetlana Volkova learned resilience as a birthright. Her parents, a librarian and a factory mechanic, saw the world shrinking around them and scraped together every resource to immigrate to America when Svetlana was 17. They landed in San Francisco, drawn by a distant cousin\u2019s promises of opportunity. The initial years were a blur of ESL classes, culture shock, and working odd jobs in the kitchens of Richmond District restaurants to help her family make ends meet.\n\nIt was during this time, while delivering groceries to an elderly Russian-speaking neighbor, that Svetlana found her calling. She witnessed firsthand the woman\u2019s isolation and vulnerability, her struggles to navigate a complex American bureaucracy. This ignited a fierce desire to advocate for those lost in the system. She enrolled at San Francisco State University, working her way through the Social Work program. Her lived experience as an immigrant gave her an empathy that couldn't be taught, and she excelled.\n\nNow 46, Svetlana is a seasoned Case Manager for Adult Protective Services. Her days are a torrent of difficult cases\u2014elder abuse, neglect, and the quiet desperation of those forgotten by a fast-paced city. Her work is emotionally taxing, but it provides a profound sense of purpose. The 4.8-mile commute on the 38-Geary MUNI bus is her time to decompress, observing the city's myriad faces from her window seat before returning to her modest apartment in the Inner Richmond.\n\nDivorced amicably a decade ago, her social life is small but strong, revolving around a few close friends\u2014a mix of fellow \u00e9migr\u00e9s and former colleagues. Her connection to San Francisco is a duality; she sees its glaring faults daily through her work, yet finds deep solace in its beauty, especially during foggy morning walks in Golden Gate Park. Svetlana\u2019s dream isn\u2019t one of wealth or grandeur. She hopes to one day have a small patio to grow her own tomatoes, to travel to see the national parks she\u2019s only read about, and to continue providing dignity and safety to the city's most vulnerable until she retires. She sought stability as a young girl and now dedicates her life to giving it to others."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was 17, just three weeks in America, when her cousin drove her to Ocean Beach. Standing before the vast, churning Pacific, the wind whipping her hair, she felt a profound terror mixed with awe. The ocean was a terrifyingly real border between her old life and this new, uncertain one. It was the first time she understood the immensity of her family\u2019s gamble. That feeling of being small against something so powerful became a permanent part of her, a source of both humility and strength.\n\n2.\nAt 19, she delivered groceries to Mrs. Petrova. The apartment smelled of borscht and mothballs. The old woman, trembling, showed Svetlana a crinkled Medicare letter she couldn\u2019t understand. In that moment, seeing the woman\u2019s fear and isolation, Svetlana\u2019s own feelings of helplessness ignited into a fierce, protective resolve. She wasn't just another lost immigrant anymore; she was a shield for someone even more vulnerable. That day, in that dim Richmond flat, her life\u2019s purpose clicked into place.\n\n3.\nIt was a decade into her career, around age 38. She\u2019d finally secured a safe care-home placement for Mr. Lim, a quiet man who had suffered terrible neglect. As they waited for the transport, he didn't speak, but reached out and timidly patted her hand twice. The simple, grateful gesture cut through all the bureaucratic noise and emotional exhaustion. It was a potent reminder that her work wasn\u2019t about winning cases, but about restoring a single person\u2019s dignity, one quiet moment at a time.\n\n4.\nThe first winter after her divorce, at 36, was bleak. A friend dragged her for a pre-dawn walk in Golden Gate Park. The fog was so thick they could barely see the path ahead. They didn\u2019t talk much, just walked, their breath pluming in the damp air. As the light slowly filtered through the cypress trees, she felt a sense of peace, not loneliness. It taught her that solitude wasn\u2019t emptiness, and that stability could be found in the quiet rhythm of a foggy morning.\n\n5.\nJust last year, on her evening commute home on the 38-Geary, she watched a young mother across the aisle trying to soothe a crying baby while reading an ESL textbook. Svetlana felt a deep, familiar ache of recognition. She saw her own mother\u2019s exhaustion, her own teenage fear, and her current clients\u2019 daily struggle all in that one woman\u2019s face. It wasn't pity she felt, but solidarity. It was a powerful, wordless reminder of why she gets on that bus every single day."
